{
  "answer": "**1. Where 'desire' fits but 'longing' does not:**  \nMirza Ghalib's couplet evokes an active, frenzied pursuit—\"This madness of *desire*, that drives me to her door\"—where *desire* captures the propulsive, almost deranged energy of repeatedly going to the beloved's threshold despite pain. *Longing* feels too passive or wistful here, lacking the sense of compulsive motion.[^1]\n\n**2. Where 'longing' fits but 'desire' is too transactional:**  \nIn this Ghalib couplet, *shauq* is rendered as *longing*: \"My heart holds, Ghalib, *longing*'s joy and separation's strain.\" *Longing* conveys the bittersweet pleasure intertwined with hijrāan (separation), a masochistic savoring of emotional ache. *Desire* implies goal-seeking or acquisition, which feels crudely transactional against this nuanced relish of sustained pain.[^2]\n\n**3. Where neither English word holds the entire weight:**  \nAllama Iqbal addresses the divine: \"I was drawn, as if by force, toward Moses’s holy height; O thirst for a single glimpse, what was your magnetic light?\" Rendered as *thirst for a glimpse* (shauq-e-deedar), it denotes an irresistible, cosmic kashish (pull)—spiritual magnetism beyond *desire*'s self-interested urge or *longing*'s melancholic wait. Neither suffices for this transcendent, involuntary attraction to the Divine vision.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 16 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/16-bask-e-dushwaar-hai-har-kaam-ka-aasaan-hona/translation/#p-9d889a).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 20 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/20-bisaat-e-ijz-mein-tha-ek-dil-yak-qatra-e-khoon-woh/translation/#p-24f098).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 10 [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/10-na-aate-humein-is-mein-takraar-kya-thi/translation/#p-c2a2e5).",
